name: 1-acetylpiperazine
Reason: The basic unit here is piperazine, which has two nitrogen atoms that can form intermolecular hydrogen bonds, contributing to an increased melting point. The acetyl group (COCH3) normally increases the melting point of a molecule due to the possibility of dipole-dipole interactions and its contribution to molecular rigidity. However, in this case, the addition of the acetyl group disrupts the ability of piperazine to form intermolecular hydrogen bonds as efficiently. We might expect the acetyl group to increase the melting point by about +20 to 30 due to its polarity and rigidity. Piperazine itself has a melting point of around 106 degrees Celsius. The loss of hydrogen bonding due to acetylation could reduce this substantially, possibly by around -70 to -90 degrees, resulting in an overall decrease. Hence, the acetyl group affects both by its own polar functional group contribution and by disrupting the hydrogen bonding capability of piperazine.
